{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526917"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14170"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14170"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.03,0.01,0.05,0.86]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6853"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99376"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6853"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81762"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45745"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99376"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive shortness of breath on exertion and fatigue. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He reports drinking 9-10 beers daily for the past eight years since his divorce.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears tired. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a displaced apex beat and a soft systolic murmur at the apex. Chest X-ray shows cardiomegaly but no lung disease . Echocardiogram reveals a dilated left ventricle (left ventricular end-diastolic volume 2.2 SD above the normal level) with reduced ejection fraction with EF ~ 35%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EECG showed normal QRS amplitude complexes with normal conduction intervals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s cardiomyopathy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypertension","Amyloidosis","Sarcoidosis","Familial mutation in sarcomere proteins","Chronic alcohol consumption"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms suggestive of dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM). The most likely cause in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic alcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s heavy beer consumption over the last eight years indicates significant alcohol intake over an extended period, which is a well-established cause of DCM. More precisely, there is alcohol-induced cardiomyopathy occurring. Alcohol-induced cardiomyopathy is defined as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConsumption of at least 80g of alcohol per day for 5+ years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeft ventricular end-diastolic diameter more than two standard deviations above the normal range, and a left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) less than 50%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExclusion of other causes of dilated cardiomyopathy, such as from hypertension and ischaemic heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloidosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes restrictive cardiomyopathy rather than dilated cardiomyopathy. It is characterized by the deposition of abnormal proteins in the heart tissue, leading to stiffening of the heart walls. This patient\u0027s presentation and echocardiogram findings are not consistent with restrictive cardiomyopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause cardiomyopathy, but it is less common than alcoholic cardiomyopathy. Cardiac sarcoidosis often presents with conduction abnormalities and arrhythmias, which are not mentioned in this case. Additionally, sarcoidosis typically affects multiple organ systems, which is not evident in this patient\u0027s presentation. Cardiac sarcoid will also have a infiltrative cardiomyopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to left ventricular hypertrophy and eventually dilated cardiomyopathy, but this patient\u0027s blood pressure is within normal limits, and there is no history of hypertension mentioned. While it remains a possibility, chronic alcohol consumption is a more likely cause given the patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamilial mutations in sarcomere proteins\u003C/strong\u003E are typically associated with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy rather than dilated cardiomyopathy. These mutations usually manifest earlier in life and often have a family history, which is not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlcoholic cardiomyopathy is a form of dilated cardiomyopathy caused by chronic, excessive alcohol consumption. It\u0027s characterised by dilatation and impaired contraction of the left or both ventricles. The mechanism involves direct toxicity of alcohol to the myocardium, as well as the effects of its metabolite, acetaldehyde. Early recognition and complete abstinence from alcohol can lead to significant improvement in cardiac function in some patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alcohol-induced cardiomyopathy may occur if there is major impact on cardiac function and consumption of at least 80g of alcohol per day for 5 or more years.","Dilated cardiomyopathy can be caused by various factors including ischemic heart disease, alcohol abuse, and viral infections."],"references":["2023 ESC Guidelines for the management of cardiomyopathies.ESC Clinical Practice Guidelines","Dom\u00ednguez F, Adler E, Garc\u00eda-Pav\u00eda P. Alcoholic cardiomyopathy: an update. Eur Heart J. 2024 Jul 9;45(26):2294-2305. doi: 10.1093/eurheartj/ehae362. PMID: 38848133; PMCID: PMC11231944."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81762"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14170"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81762"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-20T16:13:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-20T16:13:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6853"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99376"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4953"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cardiovascular Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4987","links":{"self":